[3
Date: Friday August 10, 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Guardian [edited}
<http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,3604,534619,00.html>

UK Food agency on trail of low grade meat
-----------------------------------------
Food standards chiefs yesterday announced plans to trace the exact use of
low grade meat products over the past 20 years as scientists try to
establish how many consumers have been put at risk of developing the human
form of BSE, variant CJD. Most attention will focus on the use of
mechanically recovered meat (MRM) from cattle, a prime suspect as the means
of spreading the infection from animals to people. The meat - scraps
blasted off bones - was used in sausages, pies and burgers.

[The Industry has been accused of being reluctant to provide details about
its use, which was banned only in 1995. It may be a factor in explaining
why so many young people are succumbing to the disease. New attempts will
also be made to establish what use was made of brains and spinal cord,
banned 6 years earlier. The food standards agency and the food industry say
it may be difficult to get more details, but scientists on the government's
spongiform encephalopathy advisory committee have grown increasingly
frustrated trying to get the information about MRM.

The food standards agency said manufacturers had told it they would
cooperate. "There may be some limitations on the amount and type of
information available, because there is no requirement under current food
law for meat manufacturers to keep a record of such information. "In
addition, it may be difficult to trace some meat producers and butchers
from the 1970s and 1980s."

The British Meat Manufacturers Association was not commenting in detail
yesterday, but in June, Celia Bennett, its director, said: "With the best
will in the world, it is probably going to be difficult to get the sort of
picture a scientist would want."

The scientists, as well as trying to predict the eventual size of the
epidemic of variant CJD, which has been identified in 106 Britons, are also
seeking to establish common factors in the diet. An investigation at
Queniborough, Leicestershire, near where 5 victims have lived, suggested a
combination of factors, including traditional slaughtering methods
contaminating carcasses, was responsible. Eight other clusters are also
being examined.

Estimates by the Leatherhead food research association and the meat and
livestock commission suggest that in a "worst case" during the 1980s, a
100g meat product including MRM might have contained just over a quarter of
a gram of spinal cord. MRM was widely used in schools, hospitals, prisons
and the armed services. It was also used in some baby food during the
1980s. By 1995, 6 large meat plants were still processing beef MRM. In the
early 1980s, as many as 230 000 brains may have been bought from butchers,
according to a study by the Leatherhead body some years ago.
[Byline: James Meikle, health correspondent


A similar but more emotional report was published by The Telegraph
<http://portal.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2001/08/10/nbse10.x
